//isnull().sum() checks for NaN values.
describe() gives mean, min, max, std, etc., of numeric features.
info() shows types, non-null counts, memory usage.
shape tells the number of rows and columns.//


df.dtypes

categorical_columns = ['gender', 'race/ethnicity', 'parental level of education', 'lunch', 'test preparation course']
for col in categorical_columns:
    df[col] = df[col].astype('category')

Some columns like gender and lunch type are categorical.
We convert them to the category type to reduce memory and prepare for encoding.


6 
df_encoded = pd.get_dummies(df, drop_first=True)

One-hot encoding transforms string labels into binary columns.
drop_first=True avoids the dummy variable trap





